### CHAPTER XXVII.

1\. The sage asked the spirit of wisdom (2) thus: 'Wherefore have the
people who *were* from Gâyômar*d* <span id="fr_292"></span>[1](#fn_288.md),
*and* those, too, who *were* lords and monarchs, from Hôshâng <span
id="fr_293"></span>[2](#fn_289.md), the Pê*s*dâ*d*, even unto
Vi*s*tâsp <span id="fr_294"></span>[3](#fn_290.md), the king of kings, been
such doers of *their own* wills? 3. Much benefit *was* also obtained by
them from the sacred beings, (4) *and* they have been mostly those who
*were* ungrateful unto the sacred beings, (5) and there are *some* even
who have been very ungrateful, promise-breaking, *and* sinful. 6. For
what benefit then have they *been* severally created, (7) and what
result and advantage proceeded from them?'

8\. The spirit of wisdom answered (9) thus: 'That which thou askest
concerning them, as to benefit, or *as to* the reverse <span
id="fr_295"></span>[4](#fn_291.md), thou shouldst become aware of and fully
understand. 10. Because the affairs of the world of every kind proceed
through destiny and time and the supreme decree of the self-existent
eternity (zôrvân), the king and long-continuing lord. 11. Since, at
various periods, it happens unto every one, for whom it is allotted,
just as that which is necessary to happen. 12. As even from the mutual
connection of those ancients, who are passed

<span id="page_58">p. 58</span>

away, it is manifest (13) that, ultimately, that benefit arose which was
necessary to come from them to the creatures of Aûha*r*ma*zd*.

14\. 'Because the advantage from Gâyômar*d* was this, (15) first, the
slaying of Ârzûr <span id="fr_296"></span>[1](#fn_292.md), and making
delivery of his own body, with great judiciousness, to Aharman <span
id="fr_297"></span>[2](#fn_293.md). 16. *And* the second advantage was
this, (17) that mankind and all the guardian spirits of the producers of
the renovation *of the universe*, males <span
id="fr_298"></span>[3](#fn_294.md) *and* females <span
id="fr_299"></span>[4](#fn_295.md), *were* produced from his body. 18.
*And*, thirdly, this <span id="fr_300"></span>[5](#fn_296.md), that even
the metals *were* produced *and* formed <span
id="fr_301"></span>[6](#fn_297.md) from his body <span
id="fr_302"></span>[7](#fn_298.md).

19\. 'And the advantage from Hôshâng, the Pê*s*dâ*d*, was this, (20)
that, of three parts, he slew two parts of the demons of Mâzendar <span
id="fr_303"></span>[8](#fn_299.md), who *were* destroyers of the world.

21\. 'The advantage from Tâkhmorup <span
id="fr_304"></span>[9](#fn_300.md), the well-grown,

<span id="page_59">p. 59</span>

was this, (22) that the accursed evil *one*, the wicked, *was* kept by
him thirty years as a charger <span id="fr_305"></span>[1](#fn_301.md). 23.
*And* the writing of penmanship of seven kinds, which that wicked *one*
kept in concealment, he brought out to publicity.

24\. 'The advantage from the well-flocked Yimshê*d* <span
id="fr_306"></span>[2](#fn_302), son of Vîvangha, was this, (25.md) that an
immortality of six hundred years, six months, and sixteen days <span
id="fr_307"></span>[3](#fn_303.md) is provided by him for the creatures and
creation, of every kind, of the creator Aûha*r*ma*zd*; (26) *and* they
are made unsuffering, undecaying, *and* undisturbed <span
id="fr_308"></span>[4](#fn_304). (27.md) Secondly, this <span
id="fr_309"></span>[5](#fn_305.md), that the enclosure formed by Yim <span
id="fr_310"></span>[6](#fn_306) *was* made by him; (28.md) *and* when that
rain of Malkôs <span id="fr_311"></span>[7](#fn_307.md) occurs—since *it*
is declared in revelation that mankind and

<span id="page_60">p. 60</span>

the other creatures and creations of Aûha*r*ma*zd*, the lord, are mostly
those which shall perish <span id="fr_312"></span>[1](#fn_308)—(29.md)
*one* shall afterwards open the gate of that enclosure formed by Yim,
(30) *and* the people *and* cattle, and other creatures and creations of
the creator Aûha*r*ma*zd*, shall come out from that enclosure, (31) and
arrange the world again. 32. Thirdly, (33) when <span
id="fr_313"></span>[2](#fn_309.md) he brought back the proportion of the
worldly *existences*, which that evil-producing wicked *one* <span
id="fr_314"></span>[3](#fn_310.md) had swallowed, from his belly <span
id="fr_315"></span>[4](#fn_311). Fourthly, when a goat (gôspend.md) *was*
not given by him to the demons in the character of an old man <span
id="fr_316"></span>[5](#fn_312.md).

34\. 'And the advantage from A*z*-î Dahâk, the

<span id="page_61">p. 61</span>

<span class="contnote">\[paragraph continues\]</span> Bêvarâsp <span
id="fr_317"></span>[1](#fn_313.md), and the accursed Frâsîyâk of Tûr <span
id="fr_318"></span>[1](#fn_313) was this, (35.md) that, if the dominion
should not have come to Bêvarâsp *and* Frâsîyâk, the accursed evil
spirit would then have given that dominion unto Aeshm <span
id="fr_319"></span>[2](#fn_314); (36.md) and when it would have come unto
Aeshm, it would not have been possible to take *it* away from him till
the resurrection *and* future existence, (37) for this reason, because
he has no bodily existence <span id="fr_320"></span>[3](#fn_315.md).

38\. 'And the advantage from Frê*d*ûn <span
id="fr_321"></span>[4](#fn_316) was this, (39.md) such as the vanquishing
*and* binding of A*z*-î Dahâk, the Bêvarâsp <span
id="fr_322"></span>[5](#fn_317.md), who *was* so grievously sinful. 40.
And, again too, many demons of Mâzendar <span
id="fr_323"></span>[6](#fn_318.md) were smitten by him, and expelled from
the region of Khvanîras <span id="fr_324"></span>[7](#fn_319.md).

41\. 'And the advantage from Mânû*sk*îhar <span
id="fr_325"></span>[8](#fn_320) was this, (42, 43.md) that, in revenge for
Aîrî*k*, who was his grandfather, Salm and Tû*g* *were* kept back by him
from disturbing the world <span id="fr_326"></span>[9](#fn_321.md). 44.
From the land of

<span id="page_62">p. 62</span>

<span class="contnote">\[paragraph continues\]</span>
Pa*d*ashKhvârgar <span id="fr_327"></span>[1](#fn_322.md) unto the
beginning of Dû*g*akŏ <span id="fr_328"></span>[2](#fn_323.md), such as
Frâsîyâk <span id="fr_329"></span>[3](#fn_324.md) had taken, by treaty
(pa*d*mânŏ) <span id="fr_330"></span>[4](#fn_325.md) he seized back from
Frâsîyâk, *and* brought *it* into the possession of the countries of
Irân. *And as to* the enlargement of the sea of Kânsâî <span
id="fr_331"></span>[5](#fn_326.md), such as Frâsîyâk supplied, he also
expelled the water from it.

45\. 'And the advantage from Kaî-Kavâ*d* <span
id="fr_332"></span>[6](#fn_327.md) was

<span id="page_63">p. 63</span>

this, (46) that he became a thanksgiver unto the sacred beings. 47.
Dominion, also, *was* well exercised by him, (48) *and* the family and
race of the Kayâns proceeded again from him.

49\. 'And the advantage from Sâhm\] <span
id="fr_333"></span>[1](#fn_328) was \[this\], (50.md) that the serpent
Srôvar <span id="fr_334"></span>[2](#fn_329.md) and the wolf Kapû*d* <span
id="fr_335"></span>[3](#fn_330.md), which they also call Pêhînŏ <span
id="fr_336"></span>[4](#fn_331.md), the watery demon Gandarep <span
id="fr_337"></span>[5](#fn_332.md), the bird Kamak <span
id="fr_338"></span>[6](#fn_333.md), and the deluding demon *were* slain by
him. 51. And he also performed many other great and valuable actions,
(52) and kept back much disturbance from the world, (53) *as to* which,
when one of those disturbances, in particular, should have remained
behind, it would not have been possible to produce the resurrection and
future existence.

54\. 'And the advantage from Kâî-Ûs <span
id="fr_339"></span>[7](#fn_334.md) was this,

<span id="page_64">p. 64</span>

<span class="contnote">\[paragraph continues\]</span> (55) as
Sîyâvakhsh <span id="fr_340"></span>[1](#fn_335.md) *was* produced from his
body. 56. Many other actions also proceeded from him.

57\. 'And the advantage from Sîyâvakhsh was this, (58) such as the
begetting of Kaî-Khûsrôî <span id="fr_341"></span>[2](#fn_336.md), and the
formation of Kangde*z* <span id="fr_342"></span>[3](#fn_337.md).

59\. 'And the advantage from Kaî-Khûsrôî was this, (60) such as the
slaying of Frâsîyâk <span id="fr_343"></span>[4](#fn_338), (61.md) the
extirpation of the idol-temples which *were* on the lake of
*K*ê*k*ast <span id="fr_344"></span>[5](#fn_339), (62.md) and the
management of Kangde*z*. 63. And *he* is able to do good through his
assistance of the raising of the dead <span
id="fr_345"></span>[6](#fn_340.md) *by* the restorer of the dead, the
triumphant Sôshâns <span id="fr_346"></span>[7](#fn_341.md), which is in
the future existence.

64\. 'And the advantage from Kai-Lôharâsp <span
id="fr_347"></span>[8](#fn_342.md) was

<span id="page_65">p. 65</span>

this, (65) that dominion was well exercised by him, (66) and he became a
thanksgiver unto the sacred beings. 67. He demolished the Jerusalem of
the Jews <span id="fr_348"></span>[1](#fn_343.md), and made the Jews
dispersed *and* scattered; *and* the accepter of the religion,
Kaî-Vi*s*tâsp <span id="fr_349"></span>[2](#fn_344.md), *was* produced from
his body.

68\. 'And the advantage from Vi*s*tâsp was this, (69) such as the
acceptance and solemnization of the good religion of the
Ma*zd*a-worshippers, (70) through the divine voice (bakân aêvâ*z*) *of*
the Ahunavar <span id="fr_350"></span>[3](#fn_345.md), the word of the
creator Aûha*r*ma*zd*; (71) the annihilation and destruction of the
bodies of the demons and fiends; (72) and the pleasure and comfort of
water and fire and all the angels and spirits of the worldly
*existences* <span id="fr_351"></span>[4](#fn_346.md). 73. And *he was*
full of the hope of the good and worthy, (74) through a virtuous desire
for his own determination, (75) the compensation (nô*s* da*s*nŏ) <span
id="fr_352"></span>[5](#fn_347.md) and gratification of Aûha*r*ma*zd*, with
the archangels, (76) and the affliction and destruction of Aharman and
the <span id="fr_353"></span>[6](#fn_348.md) miscreations.'

