the reign of his father, whom tradition has nearly forgotten.

<span id="fn_335"></span>[64:1](sbe24033.htm#fr_340.md) Av. Syâvarshân, the
Siyâvush of the Shâhnâmah. Though both his father and son were kings, he
did not reign himself. L19 has Kaî-Syâvash.

<span id="fn_336"></span>[64:2](sbe24033.htm#fr_341.md) See Chap. II, 95.

<span id="fn_337"></span>[64:3](sbe24033.htm#fr_342.md) Av. Kangha. A
fortified settlement said to have been 'in the direction of the east, at
many leagues from the bed of the wide-formed ocean towards that side,'
and on the frontier of Aîrân-vê*g* (see Chap. LXII, 13, Bd. XXIX, 10).

<span id="fn_338"></span>[64:4](sbe24033.htm#fr_343.md) See Chap. VIII, 29.
This name must have been applied rather to a dynasty than to a single
individual, as he reigned in Irân in the time of Mânû*sk*îhar, nearly
two hundred years earlier.

<span id="fn_339"></span>[64:5](sbe24033.htm#fr_344.md) See Chap. II, 95.

<span id="fn_340"></span>[64:6](sbe24033.htm#fr_345.md) He is expected to
assist in the renovation of the universe at the resurrection, together
with Keresâsp and other heroes (see Chap. LVII, 7, Dd. XXXVI, 3).

<span id="fn_341"></span>[64:7](sbe24033.htm#fr_346.md) See Chap. II, 95.

<span id="fn_342"></span>[64:8](sbe24033.htm#fr_347.md) Av. Kavi and
Aurva*d*aspa. He was a descendant of Kaî-Kavâ*d* in the fifth
generation, being a second cousin once removed of his predecessor,
Kaî-Khûsrôî, and reigned a hundred and twenty years (see Bd. XXXI, 25,
28, XXXIV, 7).

<span id="fn_343"></span>[65:1](sbe24033.htm#fr_348.md) Aûrî*s*alêm-i
Yahû*d*ânŏ. The first fourteen words of § 67 do not occur in the
Pâz.-Sans. version, but a corresponding statement is found in a Persian
metrical version, described by Sachau in his Contributions to the
Knowledge of Parsee Literature (J*RAS*., New Series, vol. iv, pp.
229-283), also in the works of several Arab writers of the tenth century
(see Nŏldeke, Gŏt. gel. Anz. 188 2, p. 964).

<span id="fn_344"></span>[65:2](sbe24033.htm#fr_349.md) See Chap. XIII, 14
n.

<span id="fn_345"></span>[65:3](sbe24033.htm#fr_350.md) The most sacred
formula of the Ma*zd*a-worshippers, consisting of twenty-one words,
forming three metrical lines of sixteen syllables each, beginning with
yathâ ahû vairyô, 'as a patron spirit is desirable.' It is supposed to
have been uttered by Aûha*r*ma*zd*, for the discomfiture of Aharman, on
the first appearance of that evil spirit in the universe (see Bd. I,
21).

<span id="fn_346"></span>[65:4](sbe24033.htm#fr_351.md) L19 has 'all the
angels of the spiritual and worldly *existences*.'

<span id="fn_347"></span>[65:5](sbe24033.htm#fr_352.md) L19 has u
shnâi*s*n, 'and the propitiation.'

<span id="fn_348"></span>[65:6](sbe24033.htm#fr_353.md) L19 has 'his.'

